<TITLE> Palestinian leader to pay condolence visit to Turkey </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 RAMALLAH, June 3 (bdnews24.com/AFP) - Palestinian leader Mahmud Abbas travels to Turkey next week to pay his condolences for activists killed in an Israeli attack on an aid flotilla, officials said on Thursday. Abbas would meet Turkish President Abdullah Gul on June 7, at a conference of Asian nations which Turkey is hosting, the Palestinian president's spokesman Nabil Abu Rudeina told AFP. The official Palestinian news agency WAFA said Abbas would convey his condolences over the deaths of Turks shot by Israeli commandos in an assault on an aid flotilla bound for the Hamas-run Gaza Strip on Monday. The Turkish government said on Thursday that eight Turks and a US national of Turkish origin were killed in the attack on the flotilla's lead ship, the Turkish ferry Mavi Marmara. "He will present condolences over the martyrs of freedom and will also discuss with the Turkish leadership appropriate action to respond to this crime," WAFA said, referring to the nine dead. From Turkey, Abbas will fly to the United States for talks on June 9 with President Barack Obama, Abu Rudeina said. The Palestinian leader said he would ask Obama to make "bold decisions" on Middle East peace. After the US visit Abbas will travel to Europe for meetings with Spanish Prime Minister Jose Luis Rodriguez Zapatero and French President Nicolas Sarkozy, Abbas, Abu Rudeina ad
